Saturday August 24th 2013 3:24 am -04:00,>>> 3 - - 36>>> This is because of the Operator Precedence.  Positive negative have highest precedence.  When the arithmetic expression is scanned the python grammar stipulates that it can be of the forms:a_expr ::=  m_expr | a_expr + m_expr | a_expr - m_exprThe matching case is the one on the right because the first two tokens that the interpretor scanned are 3 and -.When the scan starts on the m_expr on the right the set of rules is:m_expr ::=  u_expr | m_expr * u_expr | m_expr // u_expr | m_expr / u_expr            | m_expr % u_exprWe are then entering the first case because the first item scanned is a - so none of the other case match.Finally were encountering the rules for a u_expr:u_expr ::=  power | - u_expr | + u_expr | ~ u_exprSide note: see how were deeper in the grammar? This is why the unary - has higher precedence than the binary -.Were entering the second case of that grammar snippet because the first token is still - and whats on its left must be another u_expr.The second time around the only choice is the first one because none of the other possible first tokens are on the input stream.And the rule becomes...power ::=  primary [** u_expr]Theres a few more steps involved but the point is the expression is valid Python syntax.  Side note: when there is no way to process the input stream using the Python grammar thats when a SyntaxError is raised.For those that didnt run away and that are still interested I recommend Pr. Ullmans class Automata., Resolved,1
