Friday August 30th 2013 12:52 am -04:00,May I ask why you guys are sticking to such an historical version of the Caesars Cipher?  It certainly made sense at the time because Mr. Caesar did not have a handy tool such as ord() at his disposal and the only ordered sequence he could use was the letter sequence but if you forget that limitation you can do something thats a little bit harder to decrypt and more fun too:  >>> def caesar_encrypt(msg key = 5):...     (str int)-> str... ...     Return an encrypted version of message msg using a caesar-like cipher with...     a shift dependant on the key and the length of the string.... ...     Precondition: key is in the (arbitrary) range [O 255]... ...     ...     return .join([chr(ord(char) + key + len(msg) % key) for char in msg])... >>> def caesar_decrypt(msg key = 5):...     (str int)-> str... ...     Return an decrypted version of message msg using a caesar-like cipher with...     a reverse shift dependant on the key and the length of the string.... ...     Precondition: key is in the (arbitrary) range [O 255]... ...     ...     return .join([chr(ord(char) - key - len(msg) % key) for char in msg])... >>> scrambled = caesar_encrypt(This is a test! 255)>>> scrambledŢŶŷƁĮŷƁĮůĮƂųƁƂį>>> scrambled = caesar_encrypt(This is a test!! 255)>>> scrambled  # Notice how adding one character changes the shift.ţŷŸƂįŸƂįŰįƃŴƂƃİİ>>> caesar_decrypt(scrambled 255)This is a test!!Cheers,None,2
