Tuesday September 3rd 2013 9:06 am -04:00,Im gonna try and come up with an acceptable response but I think that ultimately this would be better handled by an instructor.  There is actually some value to the concept of not concern[ing] yourself with how it does this.  In a lot of situations you wont be able to know such a thing and will have to use the tools at your disposal either way.  To illustrate my point Im gonna try and explain how the longer function would do it:  It would be a Python function that calls the len() built-in Python function twice and compares each calls with a comparison operator. It would then based on the result of that comparison return the string passed as argument that has the biggest length.  Please note that at the time of AKs posting we were still in Week 2 so in order to answer the how he would have had to introduce Week 3 concepts.  Now that was a rather short-to-explain example but in the future you will have to use tools to solve problems and you wont at all be able to know how they work.  During the second Week of the course I coded a crude tool in Python to help with producing the PDF versions of the in-video quizzes.  I did that because without the tool the process of generating said quizzes would have been extremely painful:  Take three screenshots for each question (question correct answer explanation)Manually cut each image so that only the interesting part of the screen would remain in the image.Create a new file to hold that cut version of each image.Name each new file in a sequential manner.Convert each cut file to PDFsGlue each of those PDF files together to produce the final PDF documentNow that I have the tool I can just take screenshots and run the tool to produce the final PDF.  To code that tool I used a Python module named PyPNG.  I had to use a number of functions from that module and the point of the exercise was to do less work not more.  So I consulted the module documentation for each function and did not concern myself with how they worked only with what they were supposed to do and how I was supposed to use them and build on their work.  That kind of scenario is as I understand it one of the main points of the concept of function reuse.  I think the whole point of the exercise is to help students figure out what information is important and what information they can safely ignore.I hope I managed to answer your question somewhat.  If I didnt please dont hold that against me and please keep in mind that the CTAs in this course are people who try and help however they can but were never actually trained for this., Resolved,2
