Thursday August 29th 2013 11:42 pm -04:00,The -1 % 24 = 23 bit is due to the mathematical properties of the modulo operator actually this is one thing to watch for when you start a new programming language: not all language use the same definition of modulo operator. I once lost an hour while coding a bit of C# because of that.  But anyway the other thing to know is that this is heavily used in Video Games.  Consider an Asteroids kind of old retro video game: you are commanding an alien space battleship in a screen that is 24 positions wide.  When you are at position 23 right before colliding with the right side of the screen your position on the screen is 23 % 24 = 23 .  When you collide with the screen your position is now 24 % 24 = 0: you reappear on the left side of the screen.  When you are at position 0 on a collision course with the left side of the screen your position is 0 % 24 = 0.  And then again when you go through the left side of the screen your position is  -1 % 24 = 23: you reappear on the right side of the screen.  Cheers, Resolved,4
