Saturday August 31st 2013 8:15 am -04:00,Hello Dimitar Disclaimer: /!\ most of what follows will make no sense to most beginners reading this thread. /!\Im gonna try and answers those questions the best I can but sadly Im not a C expert so pardon me if that doesnt do the trick. 1) In Python you can consider every variable to be a pointer to a value. Variables have no type but values do. You can consider every variable to be the Python equivalent of a (void *) type pointer in C.2) In Python a function can return different kinds of values depending on what happens inside the functions body.Those built-in functions are implemented so that it returns the correct kind of value:>>> max(1.2 2.4)2.4>>> max(1 2)2>>> max(1.3 2)2>>> max(1 2.3)2.33) Unused memory locations are collected when deemed appropriate (Check out Kevins link or this one.)Heres a post where I tried to illustrate a related mechanism.Cheers, Resolved,2
