Saturday August 31st 2013 6:59 pm -04:00,I see a lot of people struggling with Assignment 1 and pasting the raw feedback summary over and over again.   This post is to explain that the feedback is not only there to tell you that something failed but also what failed and how. If you dont see well enough the screenshots copy the image address by right clicking and choosing the correct option in the contextual menu then paste it in the address bar in a new tab. I made some modifications to my personal a1.py file in order to make it fail some tests and illustrate my point please excuse my poor editing skills:   To get to the Feedback click on the view button:   Youre gonna see the awful stuff that people enjoy posting on the forums because they think that it contains meaningful information.However heres the kicker: thats not all there is to it!On that page please direct your attention to the mid-summaries link.   And then click it. This will show you a more detailed version of the feedback.When considering the next screenshot please note that every function that you are supposed to write is assigned a series of tests referred to as test_<function name>.   Here you can see that two of my functions failed: seconds_difference and hours_difference.I only introduced one error in my code. Im gonna let you speculate but at that point its pretty fair to assume that one function failing caused the other one to fail.This is specific to the code I wrote for the Assignment and it does not mean that if your function seconds_diff fails your function hours_diff should fail too. Now hey were well on our way to having a clue about what went wrong!Now is the time to get slammed in the face by the overwhelming amount of informations you get when clicking the Details link on the top right corner of the table. Brace yourself: this is rough!   As you can see for each function a number of different tests is executed.In that particular case it seems that all the tests in the docstrings are run and then some. Now you can get even more information by clicking on the FAILURE link on the right of each test report.Youll get something like this:   This gives you somewhat human-readable information about what was tested and what went wrong.  For the story I introduced a random * 0.999 in my code to derail the calculation that the grader performed.  The value on the right 12.1654etc.. is what my function returned and the value on the left is what was expected.Now if you followed the Handouts recommendations and submitted your completed steps as you went you should be able to get a grip on whats going on or at least where the problem is.   I hope this will be useful to some of you.I will update this post with a second example in a while.Cheers   , Pinned Resolved,22
