Sunday September 1st 2013 10:02 am -04:00,Hello Renée   Python uses indentation to delimit logic blocks inside a program.A function definition is such a logic block:   Everything after the functions header that is part of the function must be indented by the exact same amount of whitespaces characters.When you start writing a logic block you end the first line of that block with a colon :.Every statement coming after a colon and inside the logic block must be properly indented to the right.If the immediately following statement is not indented the interpreter will raise a SyntaxError.   When you break the level of indentation it tells the Python interpreter that the following instructions are not part of the previous logic block.Because of that youll sometime see other SyntaxErrors when you broke the indentation too soon due to the fact that some statements such as a return statement cannot appear outside of the logic block.   In about a day when Week 3 goes live another kind of logic block will be introduced: the if statement.In the same way we indent the content of function definitions well have to indent the content of the if statement.   In a lot of other programing languages logic blocks are defined by opening and closing sequences so the indentation of their content is usually not mandatory.Because its not mandatory people can feel free to indent in a very irregular manner and that tends to produce code that is very hard to read.   Cheers, Unresolved,3
