Thursday September 5th 2013 9:38 pm -04:00,The quiz is not wrong but I get why it might be confusing:  When the function is called at the moment of the assignment the sum of the numbers is printed.  It is not however returned. The fact that the sum appears on the screen is merely a side-effect.  Because the value is not returned the function exits and automatically returns None.  If youre still not convinced check this out:  >>> def sum(number1 number2):...     print(number1 + number2)... >>> result = sum(1 3)4>>> print(result)None>>> Cheers, Unresolved,1
Tuesday September 3rd 2013 3:27 pm -04:00,When the line return g(y) is executed y is first evaluated and replaced with its value: the object 1. Then the function g is called with 1 as an argument and inside of the function call the parameter x is made to point to the object  1. In python the memory management model is designed so that existing objects are not automatically duplicated but reused when possible whereas in some other language each parameter would end up in a truly local variable. At the point in the execution where your screenshot was taken both y (Edit: the y in the frame of the function f) and x are pointing to the same object value 1. If you step forward in the execution youll see that the object 1 cease to exist when the f() function call returns because the value is not needed anymore., Unresolved,2
