Thursday September 5th 2013 3:43 pm -04:00,Hey sorry about that. The way you choose to implement the functions is entirely up to you each function can actually be written so as to not depend on any other functions. It is recommended to use to_24_hour_clock because it makes you practice function reuse at least once in the Assignment but again its up to you. Both ways to go about it have their own advantages: If you go with function reuse youll minimize the risk of introducing bugs in your code. If you go with independent functions troubleshooting using the autograder will be easier. As for get_hours get_minutes and get_seconds it is important to understand that the values those functions should return are restricted in range much like it would be on a digital clock: That would be 15 hours 5 minutes 40 seconds. You would never see on that clock something like 25 hours 70 minutes 61 seconds., Unresolved,3
Thursday September 5th 2013 1:09 am -04:00,Stephen actually thats not quite how it would go: Nothing inside a function body can be executed after the program flow has reached a return statement. A function always returns one single value this is true in any programming language that I know of not only Python. This is the reason why the elif statements are not necessary here. Actually the last if statement himself is not necessary you could write:    if scheduled_time == estimated_time:        return on time    if scheduled_time < estimated_time:        return delayed    return earlyAnd the function would behave in exactly the same way. Theres only three different cases were concerned about regarding the values of scheduled_time and estimated_time. If we ever reach the second return statement its because the first condition was not met or else the function would have exited at the moment it would have reached the first return statement. And for the same reason if we ever reach the third return statement it would mean that the first two conditions checked were not met. Does that make sense?  Cheers, Resolved,1
