Saturday September 7th 2013 10:20 pm -04:00,Hey Anon What you can do is try this:Heres an example call for the function seconds_difference in Step 2:>>> seconds_difference(3600.0 1800.0)-1800.0This is the example call thats written inside the documentation string in the file a1.pyDo this in IDLE:>>> time_1 = 3600.0>>> time_2 = 1800.0Now you have two variables each with a value and its the same values they would have in the function during the example call.Then go back to the Week 1 videos about Python as a calculator and the videos about Variables. You can try and combining those variables into expressions using the arithmetic operators from the Python as a calculator video. Example:>>> time_1 + time_25400.0time_1 + time_2 is an expression and it is evaluated when you press enter as the value 5400.0. Now theres other operators available including the minus - operator. Try and use it instead of plus and see what result you get. Try different orders for the variables with different operators like time_2 + time_1 and so on. When you get an expression that evaluates to -1800.0 (the result of the function call in the example) then youll most likely have the correct expression for the function. Then go back to your a1.py file and write a return statement for the function right under the documentation string and with the same indentation as the documentation string (so 4 spaces character on the left of the keyword return). On the right of the keyword return leave a space then write the expression you found that evaluates to -1800.0. Then save the file using either the menu or CTRL + S. Next either use Run -> Run module or copy all the code for the function seconds_difference by selecting it then using CTRL + C and paste it into IDLE using CTRL + V then hit enter until you get back the prompt >>>.  Once thats done go back to your file and copy an example call then paste it into IDLE and check that it returns the correct value according to the Examples.  Do that for each example call in the documentation string.  When thats done and you got the right value each time go to the Assignment page click the Submit button on the bottom-right. Using the dialog that opens select your file a1.py and make sure that is the correct file that you modified. Then click Open and then Submit again. When thats done go back to the Assignment page and click the View button at the bottom right and you should see that your function seconds_difference passed some tests and got you some points. Then go back to your code and re-read the instructions about the function from the handout read again the function description from the documentation string and understand why the code you wrote make sense.  Then you should be able to go to Step 3., Unresolved,0
