Friday September 13th 2013 1:55 pm -04:00,This exercise is about function reuse and how to apply a function to every characters in a string. A good example of a very similar use case is the implementation of the encryption step of a shift cipher. A shift cipher works by replacing each character in the input string by the character obtained if the first character is shifted by a number of places. So for example A becomes B with a shift of 1. A shift cipher with a constant shift key of 1 could be implemented like this: def shift_one(char):     (str) -> str    Returns the character obtained by shifting char one time to the right.    >>> shift_one(A)    B    >>> shift_one(B)    C        # Get the number corresponding to the character add 1 to it    #  and returns the character corresponding to that new number.    return chr(ord(char) + 1)def get_encrypted_message(message):     (str) -> str    Returns an encrypted version of message obtained by shifting every    character one place to the right.    >>> get_encrypted_message(AB)    BC    >>> get_encrypted_message(BC)    CD        output =                            # Initialize the accumulator variable.    for char in message:                  # For every character in message...        output = output + shift_one(char)     # ...add the shifted char to output.    return output                         # When every char was added return the result.>>> get_encrypted_message(This is a test!)Uijt!jt!b!uftuNow for the get_complementary_sequence code instead of the shift_one function you would be using the get_complementary function., Resolved,5
